t: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def longestEqualSubarray(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve this problem, we can use a sliding window approach. The idea is to maintain a window of elements where we can delete at most `k` elements to make all elements in the window equal. We'll use a dictionary to keep track of the frequency of each number within the current window. The goal is to maximize the size of this window while ensuring that the number of deletions required does not exceed `k`.\n\nHere's the step-by-step approach:\n\n1. Initialize a dictionary `freq` to keep track of the frequency of each number in the current window.\n2. Use two pointers, `left` and `right`, to represent the current window. Start both at the beginning of the array.\n3. Expand the window by moving the `right` pointer and update the frequency of the current element.\n4. Calculate the number of deletions required to make all elements in the window equal. This is the size of the window minus the frequency of the most frequent element in the window.\n5. If the number of deletions exceeds `k`, shrink the window from the left by moving the `left` pointer and updating the frequency accordingly.\n6. Keep track of the maximum window size that satisfies the condition.\n\nHere's the implementation of the above approach:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def longestEqualSubarray(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        freq = {}\n        left = 0\n        max_length = 0\n        most_frequent = 0\n        \n        for right in range(len(nums)):\n            num = nums[right]\n            if num in freq:\n                freq[num] += 1\n            else:\n                freq[num] = 1\n            \n            most_frequent = max(most_frequent, freq[num])\n            \n            # Calculate the current window size\n            window_size = right - left + 1\n            \n            # Calculate the number of deletions needed\n            deletions_needed = window_size - most_frequent\n            \n            # If deletions needed exceed k, shrink the window from the left\n            if deletions_needed > k:\n                freq[nums[left]] -= 1\n                if freq[nums[left]] == 0:\n                    del freq[nums[left]]\n                left += 1\n            \n            # Update the maximum length of the equal subarray\n            max_length = max(max_length, window_size - deletions_needed)\n        \n        return max_length\n\n# Example usage:\n# sol = Solution()\n# print(sol.longestEqualSubarray([1,3,2,3,1,3], 3))  # Output: 3\n# print(sol.longestEqualSubarray([1,1,2,2,1,1], 2))  # Output: 4\n```\n\nThis code efficiently finds the longest equal subarray after deleting at most `k` elements using a sliding window approach. The time complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the input array, as each element is processed at most twice (once when expanding the window and once when shrinking it). The space complexity is O(n) due to the frequency dictionary.", "estimated_date": 1692489600000}